node.text:
Lemeki begins each morning quite literally sniffing out adventure, poking her trunk through her stockade to investigate the goings-on at our Kaluku Neonate Nursery. After her morning milk bottle, she’s ready to explore Tsavo with her Keepers. Lemeki and her little friends spend the day racing up and down the beach, spying on wild elephants and other creatures, and cavorting in the mud bath.

As she sun begins to sink in the sky, Lemeki and co. return to the stockade compound for bed. While the other orphans are eager to rest, it always takes our curious girl a little while to move into sleep mode. She remains on high alert for any interesting activity happening in the stockade area, ending her day just as she starts it. Passing Keepers are treated to a chorus of rumbles, but they know exactly how to settle her down: “lala, Lemeki, lala” — which means “sleep, Lemeki, sleep!” in Swalili. After establishing that everyone else is calling it a night, our little Lemeki finally succumbs to bedtime herself. 

Want to learn more about Lemeki and how to support her future?  Click our link in bio or visit:

node.text:
This brave little calf has overcome great tragedy.  In early May, a gravely injured elephant was reported in the Chyulus. Her leg was shattered, leaving her all but immobile and marooned on a waterless lava slope. To further compound an already devastating situation, the female in question was the mother of an infant, milk-dependent calf. 

With no chance of recovery, KWS made the difficult decision to euthanise the mother and rescue her youngest calf. Her eldest calf was about seven years old and no longer milk-dependent. He would remain in the company of two adult bulls who were serving as guardians of the family, so he could re-join the herd in the area.

Esoit is the Maa word for “rock,” after the area where he was rescued — and it is a fitting name in more ways than one! This little boy has been a pillar of strength amidst extremely traumatic circumstances. He immediately embraced Nursery life and has become fast friends with Roho. You might notice a curious feature about Esoit: His right hind knee is markedly calcified, indicating an earlier, healed injury. Luckily, it doesn’t seem to hold him back in any way and he whizzes around just as adeptly as the other orphans!

While nothing can replace his lost mother, Esoit will still grow up knowing the love and support of a family. You can join his herd and support his reintegration journey this #FosterFriday by adopting him. Learn more via our link in today’s Stories or visit:
sheldrickwildlifetrust.org/orphans/esoit

Giraffes are one of the most iconic sights of the African savanna, but we must never take their presence for granted: In what has been coined a “silent extinction,” giraffe populations have plummeted 30% since the 1980s, with just 117,000 remaining in the wild. Habitat loss is driving force behind their disappearance, while poaching has emerged as another grave threat. 

Kiko is a survivor. Orphaned when he was just a week old, he was found alone in an area of increased human activity. We rescued him and Kiko spent the first five years of his life at our Nairobi Nursery.  Last year, graduated to Sirikoi in the Lewa Wildlife Conservancy, where he will continue his reintegration journey. Our quirky giraffe who was raised among elephants is now befriending his own kind. When he is ready, Kiko will join wild reticulated giraffe populations. 

As we celebrate Kiko, please consider donating to help us combat habitat loss, which is the number one threat to giraffes. Contributions to our Saving Habitats Match Appeal will be doubled, which means any amount you give will have 2x the impact in helping us save wild spaces before they are lost forever. sheldrickwildlifetrust.org/campaigns/saving-habitats

What better way to start a new week than by joining the rescued orphan elephants at our Nairobi Nursery. Their day starts early, around 6am, with bottles of warm milk formula, before it's time to catch up with their friends from the neighbouring stables and head out into the bush to explore.

Kirsty is joining Keeper Julius, and together they'll introduce us to the members of this special herd, while talking about the reasons they came to need our help and how it is we raise the elephants so that they can return to a fully wild life when grown.  After the live, you can learn more about our work on our website, where you can also choose to adopt one of the orphans: Helping us provide them the care they need and allowing you to become a part of their journey back to the wild (website link in bio)

node.text:
The moment we rescue an orphaned elephant, we are looking ahead — not just days and weeks ahead, but decades ahead, to the wild lives they will eventually lead. After all, these blanket-clad babies will one day roam the wilds of Kenya, reclaiming their place as giants of the plains. 

That’s where our Saving Habitats project comes in: We are securing vast tracks of land across Kenya, ensuring that the orphans in our care — and all creatures — have a protected space to call home. Our new matched giving appeal is your chance to get involved in this vital endeavour. Thanks to a generous partner, donations made directly to our Saving Habitats Appeal will be doubled up to $250,000 — which means that we have the opportunity to raise an astounding $500,00 in support of habitat preservation. 

Play your part and donate today — every dollar makes an enormous difference! See our link in bio or visit:

node.text:
Graduations are always poignant experiences, but especially for our mini matriarchs. These remarkable elephants, who have put so much into nurturing younger orphans, are still very much babies themselves. Graduations give them the opportunity to learn from older friends and ultimately reclaim their place in the wild.

And so, while Maisha was our beloved leader of the Nursery herd, we knew it was time for her to focus on her own personal growth — and that our Ithumba Reintegration Unit in Tsavo East would be a most fitting destination. Maisha’s graduation partner would be her dear friend and co-mini matriarch, Nabulu.

As you can see, the whole affair went off without a hitch, and both girls are thoroughly enjoying Ithumba life. Head over to our website to read about the graduation in detail — link in today’s stories or visit:
sheldrickwildlifetrust.org/news/updates/maisha-nabulu-to-ithumba

A suspected spear wound threatened to put this fellow out of commission, but thanks to timely veterinary intervention, he is once again roaming the plains of Amboseli. It all unfolded yesterday, when Big Life alerted us of elephant with an injured from leg. With aerial support from our Sky Vets initiative, our SWT/KWS Amboseli Mobile Vet Unit mobilized a treatment. After darting the patient from our helicopter, Dr Kariuki thoroughly cleaned out the wound and administered  antibiotics and anti-inflammatories. The bull was sent off with a good prognosis for recovery, but our teams will continue to monitor him in case he needs follow-up care. (Hence the number on his side, which will make it easy for our team to identify him from the air.)

These orphans have come so far since they were rescued: gentle Maktao, who was found in elephant-hostile territory; plucky Kiasa, who sought refuge with two adult bulls; brave Kiombo, who tried to fend for himself after losing his mother. As we began to plan this trio’s future, we knew that Umani Springs would be the perfect next step. Its lush forest environment, which connects to the Amboseli and Tsavo ecosystems, makes it a coveted destination for any elephant. Their arrival would also be a healing gift for the Umani Springs herd, who was left so heartbroken by Luggard’s passing.

Travel back to two weeks ago, when Maktao, Kiasa, and Kiombo took their first steps in their new home. This graduation marks the beginning of the rest of their lives. Umani Springs will serve as a home base for these three orphans learn the ways of the wild, until they are ready to transition from our care. node.text:
When we talk about wild babies born to our ex orphans, a tiny elephant probably comes to mind. While Mwende once fit this description, she’s now a majestic girl of nine years old — and perhaps not too far off from becoming a mother herself!

Mwende is only here today because we were able to rescue her mum, Mulika, at the turn of the millennium. Mulika thrived in our care and was eventually reintegrated into the wilds of Tsavo, where she gave birth to Mwende in 2011. It’s been such a privilege to watch this family blossom over the intervening decade.

node.text:
Hot on the heels of Kiasa, Maktao, and Kiombo’s graduation earlier this week, our Nursery big girls took the next step in their journey back to the wild. They hit the road early and arrived at our Ithumba Reintegration Unit just before 8am. Their old friends from the Nursery — namely Ambo, Sattao, Musiara, Dololo, and Jotto — were the first to greet them, but soon the whole Ithumba herd had enveloped them in a very warm welcome. Both Maisha and Nabulu acted like absolute pros. In fact, they were so nonchalant about their new home that they dove right into the Ithumba pool, as if they had been doing it their whole lives!

In the coming days, we will share more about their graduation, but we wanted to make sure you were involved in this special milestone — milestones that are only made possible through your support. Thank you for adopting, donating, and helping us give orphaned elephants like Maisha and Nabulu the future they deserve.

node.text:
It must be said that raising Lapa is not for the faint of heart! He is an absolute rascal: Within weeks of his birth, he was diving into water troughs, chasing after elephants ten times his size, and generally causing mayhem. Now, with over a year on earth under his belt, this little boy is getting even more feisty with age. Fortunately, his mother is an absolute pro (and supported by a very diligent coterie of nannies!). Lenana was just a baby when her own mother died before her eyes, and she grew up in our care. However, seeing how proficiently she parents Lapa, you would never guess that she was raised by humans. Seeing orphans like Lenana become mothers are our proudest success stories.

_________

node.text:
At seven years old, Mwashoti is becoming quite a big bull — but he still fancies himself the baby of the Umani herd! As such, the arrival of Nursery graduates Kiasa, Maktao, and Kiombo really bothered him. He resorted to all sorts of insociable hijinks to express his displeasure, from chasing Kiasa to pulling Maktao’s tail. The final straw was when he found that Kiombo had moved into his and Sonje’s stockade. After several unsuccessful attempts to evict the younger bull, Mwashoti went off in a huff and spent several nights out in the forest with the semi-independent orphans. This time away seemed to give him perspective on the situation, and now he’s being much more accepting towards the trio of newcomers. As an added bonus, their arrival has also encouraged Mwashoti to embark on his own reintegration journey, which is a wonderful development.

_________

For Esoit, all the world’s a jungle gym! He has only been at the Nursery for two months, but he has settled in extraordinarily well. With so many orphans in the mix, he sometimes gets so excited and confused as to who he should play with! This day’s playmate of choice was Naboishu. It’s actually funny to see Esoit climbing all over the bigger bull, because Naboishu is usually the one pushing everyone else around.

While he is a picture of joy today, Esoit came to us through extremely tragic circumstances. To learn more about his story and how you can support his m future through an adoption, click our link in bio 🐘

node.text:
Bondeni is barreling into the week! He is always in “go” mode, from the very moment he wakes up. One morning, he was so eager to get going that he started banging his stable door and climbing up to see outside. He was making such a commotion that the Keepers decided to let him out early, so the other orphans could wake up in peace. Once he was outside, however, Bondeni seemed a little disappointed to find that everyone else was still in their stables.  He busied himself by doing his rounds, poking his trunk into his friends’ bedrooms, until it was time for the whole herd to head out into the forest together.

Want to learn more about Bondeni and how he came into our care? Click our link in bio or visit:
sheldrickwildlifetrust.org/orphans/bondeni

node.text:
What’s wrong with this picture? Look closely, and you’ll see a wire snare wrapped around this lion cub’s neck. Although she was protected by her pride, the wound must have been extremely painful and was causing her condition to deteriorate. Our SWT/KWS Meru Mobile Vet Unit darted the patient and gently pushed away the eight other lions, so they could safely move forward with treatment. Fortunately, everything went smoothly and the cub was soon back by her pride’s side. It was certainly a successful weekend for lifesaving veterinary operations!

node.text:
To earn the love of an elephant is one of the greatest privileges on earth. For this remarkable species — and especially for our orphans — family bonds last a lifetime. We were poignantly reminded of this fact last week, when this majestic fellow showed up at Ithumba. Given how remarkably friendly and comfortable he was around our Head Keeper Benjamin, he is almost certainly a grown orphan we rescued, raised, and reintegrated back to the wild. We believe he could be Imenti, who we rescued as a newborn back in 1994 after his mother was killed by poachers. Imenti is now 27 years old and has been living wild for nearly two decades.

It has been many, many years since Imenti’s last visit — but as we are reminded time and again, our orphans never forget the people who saw them through their darkest days. We feel enormously honored to be part of these creatures’ lives and to see them thriving as wild elephants, as nature always intended.

As Angela Sheldrick puts it, “All creatures are capable of empathy and understanding. It falls upon us to connect with and respect the other creatures with whom we share our home.” This doesn’t only apply to the orphans we raise, but all the remarkable creatures we encounter. In her latest Field Notes article, she shines a spotlight on three extraordinary stories of animals seeking out help from humans in times of need. To read more, see our link in today’s stories or visit:
sheldrickwildlifetrust.org/news/fieldnotes/june-2021

Ndotto and Ivia’s friendship is turning heads across Tsavo! When this wild herd approached the Voi water trough for a drink, the matriarch couldn’t help but give the elephant and buffalo a curious glance. This is nothing new to us: Every afternoon, while the other Voi orphans wallow in the mud or enjoy a dust bath after their midday milk feed, Ndotto and his buffalo friend are usually embroiled in spirited sparring matches.

node.text:
Lemeki begins each morning quite literally sniffing out adventure, poking her trunk through her stockade to investigate the goings-on at our Kaluku Neonate Nursery. After her morning milk bottle, she’s ready to explore Tsavo with her Keepers. Lemeki and her little friends spend the day racing up and down the beach, spying on wild elephants and other creatures, and cavorting in the mud bath.

As she sun begins to sink in the sky, Lemeki and co. return to the stockade compound for bed. While the other orphans are eager to rest, it always takes our curious girl a little while to move into sleep mode. She remains on high alert for any interesting activity happening in the stockade area, ending her day just as she starts it. Passing Keepers are treated to a chorus of rumbles, but they know exactly how to settle her down: “lala, Lemeki, lala” — which means “sleep, Lemeki, sleep!” in Swalili. After establishing that everyone else is calling it a night, our little Lemeki finally succumbs to bedtime herself.

node.text:
Rhinos are solitary by nature, but Maxwell always knows how to keep busy. When he’s not napping, snacking, or strolling around, he likes to tease the Nursery’s resident wild warthogs. When they daringly sneak into his stockade to snack on his lucerne pellets, Maxwell deliberately taunts them and sends them scattering in all directions. Satisfied with his game, he then trots up to the top half of his stockade and complacently flops down atop his pellets for a nap. This effectively deters any would-be thieves from trying their luck again!

We rescued Maxwell 14 years ago, after he was found alone and afraid in Nairobi National Park. It transpired that he was permanently blind, as a result of a congenital eye condition. For that reason, he has a forever home with us. You can become part of Maxwell’s family this #FosterFriday by adopting him — link in bio/stories to learn more 🦏

Ngasha is limbering up for a big night out on the town! The Keepers have nicknamed him and the other semi-independent Umani orphans “the nightclubbers” — and for good reason! They have raucous times out in the forest, learning the ways of the wild and fraternizing with local herds. Ngasha picked up some bad habits from his wild friends and became quite a pest for a spell, relentlessly chasing around the older girls. He seemed to learn his lesson when one particularly amorous pursuit of Murera resulted in him lightly spraining his leg. He healed quickly, and it also seemed to reform his character somewhat: He is now much more polite around the dependent herd!

To learn more about Ngasha and the other members of our Umani herd, click our link in bio or visit:

node.text:
Over the years, a number of injured wild elephants have appeared at our stockades seeking help. This is a deeply humbling experience; while the majority of them were harmed by the human hand, they can still distinguish that we are a safe haven, there to offer a lifeline when they need it most.
 
Such was the case this past Saturday when a handsome wild bull showed up at our Ithumba Reintegration Unit. He was sporting a poisoned arrow wound that, judging by its deeply septic state was several weeks old.

As it turns out, this wasn’t the only lifesaving treatment on the docket that weekend: The very next day, our SWT/KWS Tsavo Mobile Vet Unjt headed to the slopes of the Chyulus to treat a speared elephant that had been reported by Big Life. To find out how these operations unfolded, see the link in today’s stories or visit:
sheldrickwildlifetrust.org/news/updates/two-bulls-call-for-help

node.text:
What a difference five months can make! When we rescued Rama, he was very withdrawn and gaunt. It’s easy to understand why: He had been on his own for several weeks, in what must have been a very lonely and frightening experience. While he is shy by nature, this sweet boy has really settled into the Nursery herd. You might notice his interesting gait — he was born with bowlegs — but his mobility has improved enormously and he now zips around with admirable speed. We are so pleased with Rama’s progress thus far!

Rama is an inspirational elephant who has already overcome so much. To discover his story, click our link in bio or visit:
sheldrickwildlifetrust.org/orphans/rama

node.text:
Ever since Maktao graduated from the Nursery, Mukkoka has taken on the role of “kind uncle” of the herd. He’s the oldest bull in the group, but also the gentlest. Mukkoka has had an especially beneficial influence on Naboishu. This young bull is becoming a bit of an upstart, but Mukkoka knows exactly how to keep him in line — be it putting him in a friendly headlock if he gets carried away or indulging him in a spirited pushing match. However, whenever Naboishu crosses the line and bullies the other orphans, Mukkoka is the first to banish him away from the herd for a brief time-out. We’re very impressed by the empathy and leadership of this three-year-old elephant.
